                    The Complete Wordpress Website Business Course - Gregg Davis

                    Section: 1 - About this Course
1 - What You Need for this Course
Quick intro to course
Wordpress is open source
The instrucor gives a list of tools needed
- Atom or Notepad++
- Ftp, fireftp or filezilla
- GIMP, Pixler, PhotR

2 - What You'll Learn in this Course
A run through of what will be learned in the course
CMS - Content Management System
Huge community of plugins and themes
A very quick run through of the features of a wordpress installation

3 - WordPress Business Basics - Tools
Tools needed to setup the business site
Explanations of terms such as Hosting, URL Domain Name etc
Dont use word processor for text formatting
Using Excel or Google spreadsheet templates, 3rd party templates are available
Use PDF for send invoices to clients due to them not being editable
Paypal Business Account is recommended to be used for clients to pay 


                    Section: 2 - Prepare Hosting, Servers, and Install WordPress
1 - Website Hosting and Development Options
An exploration of the different hosting options available
  - Shared
  - Dedicated
  - VPS
  - Cloud
 Recommended to have have hosting as part of your sales options due to the recurring income that it can provide

2 - Your Free SiteGround Hosting Account
How to setup a free account with Siteground Hosting (exclusive deal as part of the course)
Some settings are changed by the instructor eg time
Permalinks are changed to posts which are best for SEO urposes

3 - Your Free Flywheel Hosting Account
How to setup a free account with Flywheel Hosting (exclusive deal as part of the course)
Flywheel offers managed Wordpress hosting
You will need to verify by either credit card or sms text message
Same preferences setup
Limit login attempts plugin installed by default

4 - Install WordPress Manually
Installing WP on local machine
Course instructor uses MAMP but there are multiple alternatives such as XAMPP

5 - Explore WordPress Files and Database
Akismet is used to stop spam
WP-Content is where plugins etc go
On Siteground the Jetpack plugin is installed by default
You can change url on PHPMyAdmin, which can help recover DNS errors
Editing themes using functions.php has best practice
Wordpress has a built in editor for editing files
Always have a backup copy of any file being edited
Dont use admin as user name
You can change username from within PHPMyAdmin

6 - Get Your Sandbox
As part of the course there is a student sandbox available for comletion of the exercises during the course
List of sandbox installed plugins

7 - WordPress Defaults
Conecntrating on local installation
Wordpress has several default settings which should be changed
Clicking appearence -> themes shows themes
Wordpress ships with 2 default plugins, they need to be activated
Plugin can be deleted easily
Akismet is recommended when site is finished



                     Section 3: - Build a Brochure Site
1 - Create a New WordPress Installation
First practical project of the course
Simple brochure site
Fresh install of WP either locally or on Siteground
Settings as per previous setup videos
Remote installation not using WP wizard has more steps than local install

2 - Salts and Plugins
Keys and salts are at the end of the wp-config file
Using the link in the wp-config file you can auto generate keys by copying and pasting url in file
The process is the same is the local installation
Flywheel is not set up as the wp-config file is managed privately, you cannot access it
SFTP - Secure ftp
4 plugins has to be installed
 - Contact Form - Contact Form 7
 - Email protection - Email Address Encoder -- Converts address to hex to avoid bot-harvesting
 - Google Analytics - Google Analyticator
 - Google Maps - WP Google Maps
Plugins in wp-content folder
A few things to check 
 - Compatible with your WP version
 - Updated Regularly
 - How many installs

3 - Static Homepage and Posts
Customise the front page of the site
Blockquote can be removed in editor
Images should be edited to as small as possible
Use the add media button to add images then insert in page
Appearance -> Customise opens up an editor
Site title & tagline can be edited 
Logo can be added by clicking add logo, dimensions are 240 x 240
Site Icon (Favicon) can be added through site icon, imensions are 512 x 512
Site Icon should be simple
Posts can be 
 - Categorized
 - Formatted
 - Timestamped

4 - Interior Pages, Navigation and Sidebar
To add pages
 - Pages -> Add New
To Add Page Links to Navigation
 - Appearence -> Menus
 - Enter Menu Name -> Create Menu -> Select Pages to be added to menu -> Add to Menu
Check Primary Menu Box
http://www.lipsum.com - Dummy Text
Dummy Text is good for placeholding
 -> Save Menu

Bold indicates page you are on
Rollover is blue as standard

You can also use 
 - Customise -> Menus

You can setup dropdown menus in the customiser, the menu items will be slightly indented
Use the arrows to manouver menu items

Sidebar & Footer controlled using widgets
- Appearence -> Widgets or -- Customise -> Widgets
Remove Each widget by opening and clicking remove
Sidebar also called widget area
Widgets can be dragged and dropped

5 - Configure Contact Form
Configuring the previously installed contact form
Screen Options has drop down menu
Contact -> Contact Forms -> Open the pre-setup form
4 tabs
 - Form -- Contains Form information
 - Mail -- Allows you to set up emailing
 - Messages -- A list of messages
 - Additional Settings -- Multiple sets of additional settings

When surrounded by square brackets you can just paste the form into the page

Cant use email server testing on localhost
You can build site on localhost and test when site is migrated
There is a form tag generator (All standard HTML elements
reCaptcha is available to stop spamming
Use text widget to contact form to sidebar on all pages
Inactive widgets keep all their settings and meybe added in later

6 - Configure Google Maps
Embedding a map on the contact page
Go to Maps -> Maps
Plugin allows 1 map using free edition
All maps now require a Javascript API key, testing can be done with the temporary one
** Some issues with Google Maps plugin
You can add markers & add addresses to markers
Map Size can also be sized manually or at responsive size
In settings you can get short code and add it to pages
Styling does not transfer to widgets, you will have to add styling
Plugin for Google Maps provides widgets
Change to WP Google Map Plugin by Flippercode
You will need to experiment with zoom levels


7 - Configure Google Analytics
Google Analytics is free & tracks website visitors
If client will be logging in themselves then setup an account for them
You need a google account to setup analytics account
You won't have a URL if developing locally
Leave defaults & agree to T&C
UA code works with plugins for adding Analytics
JS script tag also available to add to code
You will have to decide if you will be tracking all of the site pages
Authenticate plugins with google



